  "text": "Apache Kafka implements a comprehensive service lifecycle management pattern using coordinated initialization and shutdown of dependent services. The pattern centers around the BrokerServer (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/BrokerServer.scala) which orchestrates multiple service instances with strict ordering guarantees.\n\n## Core Lifecycle Architecture\n\n### Primary Orchestrator: BrokerServer\nThe BrokerServer class manages the complete lifecycle of a Kafka broker, implementing the startup() and shutdown() methods defined by the KafkaBroker interface (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/KafkaBroker.scala). The startup method follows a precise initialization sequence where services are started in dependency order, while shutdown reverses this order to ensure graceful teardown.\n\n### Lifecycle Manager: BrokerLifecycleManager\nBrokerLifecycleManager (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/BrokerLifecycleManager.scala) manages the broker state transitions throughout the lifecycle. It coordinates with the controller quorum and handles broker registration, metadata synchronization, and state management. The manager uses an event queue paradigm for thread-safe state management.\n\n## Coordinator Services Pattern\n\nKafka implements multiple coordinator services following a consistent Startable/Stoppable pattern:\n\n### GroupCoordinator Service\n- **Interface**: GroupCoordinator (group-coordinator/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/coordinator/group/GroupCoordinator.java)\n- **Implementation**: GroupCoordinatorService (group-coordinator/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/coordinator/group/GroupCoordinatorService.java)\n- **Lifecycle Methods**: startup(IntSupplier) and shutdown()\n- The startup method accepts an IntSupplier to retrieve the number of partitions in __consumer_offsets topic\n- The shutdown method sets isActive flag to false and closes runtime, metrics, and config manager\n- Uses AtomicBoolean for thread-safe state management\n\n### ShareCoordinator Service\n- **Interface**: ShareCoordinator (share-coordinator/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/coordinator/share/ShareCoordinator.java)\n- **Implementation**: ShareCoordinatorService (share-coordinator/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/coordinator/share/ShareCoordinatorService.java)\n- **Lifecycle Methods**: startup(IntSupplier) and shutdown()\n- Similar pattern to GroupCoordinator with state management via AtomicBoolean\n\n### TransactionCoordinator Service\n- **Class**: TransactionCoordinator (core/src/main/scala/kafka/coordinator/transaction/TransactionCoordinator.scala)\n- **Lifecycle Methods**: startup(retrieveTransactionTopicPartitionCount, enableTransactionalIdExpiration) and shutdown()\n- Manages transaction state and producer ID allocation\n- Coordinates with TransactionStateManager and TransactionMarkerChannelManager\n\n## Service Startup Ordering\n\nThe BrokerServer.startup() method (lines 189-607) initializes services in the following order:\n\n1. **Shared Server Initialization**: sharedServer.startForBroker()\n2. **Configuration**: Load dynamic broker configs and quota managers\n3. **Scheduler**: Create and start KafkaScheduler for background tasks\n4. **Metadata Cache**: Initialize KRaftMetadataCache\n5. **Log Manager**: Create LogManager (deferred startup)\n6. **Lifecycle Manager**: Create BrokerLifecycleManager\n7. **Network Components**: Initialize socket server, credential provider, and API version manager\n8. **Alter Partition Manager**: Create and start AlterPartitionManager\n9. **Replica Manager**: Create ReplicaManager\n10. **Token Manager**: Create DelegationTokenManager\n11. **Authorizer**: Load authorizer plugin\n12. **Config Manager**: Initialize GroupConfigManager\n13. **Coordinator Services**: Create ShareCoordinator and GroupCoordinator\n14. **Transaction Coordinator**: Create TransactionCoordinator\n15. **Metadata Publishers**: Install all metadata publishers\n16. **Lifecycle Manager Start**: Start BrokerLifecycleManager with registration\n17. **Metadata Synchronization**: Wait for initial catch-up and metadata publishing\n18. **Socket Server**: Enable request processing\n\n## Service Shutdown Ordering\n\nThe BrokerServer.shutdown() method (lines 729-843) stops services in REVERSE order to ensure dependencies are respected:\n\n1. **Controlled Shutdown**: Begin controlled shutdown if enabled\n2. **Request Processing**: Stop socket server request processing\n3. **Metadata Publishers**: Remove and close all metadata publishers\n4. **Request Handlers**: Shutdown data plane request handler pool and processor\n5. **Scheduler**: Shutdown KafkaScheduler (early to prevent concurrent resource access)\n6. **Transaction Coordinator**: Shutdown transaction coordinator\n7. **Config Manager & Coordinators**: Close group config manager, group coordinator, and share coordinator\n8. **Assignment Manager**: Close assignments manager\n9. **Replica Manager**: Shutdown replica manager\n10. **Alter Partition Manager**: Shutdown alter partition manager\n11. **Forwarding Manager**: Close forwarding manager\n12. **Controller Channel**: Shutdown client-to-controller channel manager\n13. **Log Manager**: Shutdown log manager\n14. **Remote Log Manager**: Close remote log manager\n15. **Quota Managers**: Shutdown quota managers\n16. **Socket Server**: Shutdown socket server\n17. **Cleanup**: Close broker topic stats and share partition manager\n18. **State Persister**: Stop share state persister\n19. **Lifecycle Manager**: Close lifecycle manager\n\n## Concurrency and Error Handling\n\nThe pattern uses several mechanisms for safe concurrent execution:\n- **CoreUtils.swallow()**: Catches and logs exceptions during shutdown to ensure all services are shutdown\n- **AtomicBoolean**: Used for thread-safe state flags in coordinators\n- **ReentrantLock**: Used in BrokerServer for status management (lines 101-103)\n- **CompletableFuture**: Used for asynchronous operations and synchronization points\n\n## Key Service Dependencies\n\nThe ReplicaManager (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/ReplicaManager.scala) has startup() at line 336 and shutdown() methods that manage partition replicas and ISR expirations.\n\nThe LogManager (core/src/main/scala/kafka/log/LogManager.scala) manages log segments and has startup() and shutdown() methods for disk I/O operations.\n\nThe BrokerMetadataPublisher (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/metadata/BrokerMetadataPublisher.scala) receives metadata updates and triggers coordinator startup through finishInitializingReplicaManager() once the ReplicaManager is ready.\n\n## Implementation Details\n\nEach coordinator service follows a builder pattern for construction and uses an internal isActive AtomicBoolean flag to track state. The startup() methods are idempotent—if called when already active, they log a warning and return. The shutdown() methods perform the reverse operation, ensuring clean resource deallocation.\n\nThe BrokerLifecycleManager acts as the state hub, managing broker registration with the KRaft quorum and exposing futures for state transitions that other components wait on. This ensures no service attempts to serve requests before the broker is in a proper state.\n\nThe pattern exemplifies the Graceful Shutdown pattern where dependent services are stopped in reverse order of initialization, with comprehensive error handling using swallow() to ensure partial failures don't prevent complete shutdown."
